5. UX & Interface Design
The app should feel like a native Mac utility — not a web app in a window. It should invoke macOS conventions:
system fonts, native notifications, and a menu bar presence. No onboarding required after initial setup.
Persistent Mode Options
Mode Description
Menu bar app (recommended) Icon in the top bar; click to expand dropdown panel. Least intrusive — no windows to
manage.
Floating window Pinned to a Mission Control Space; always visible in a dedicated desktop.
Notification Center widget Native macOS widget; no separate window needed.
Main Dashboard Layout
The dropdown panel renders in this order, top to bottom:
• Header bar: app name, sync status indicator, and settings gear icon
• Urgency sections: Overdue (red), Due Today, Due Tomorrow, This Week, Coming Up
• Each assignment row: course color dot → assignment name → due time → submission badge
• Footer: last synced timestamp and manual refresh button
Key UX Behaviors
Behavior Specification
Wake behavior On wake from sleep, auto-sync fires. Menu bar badge updates immediately.
Dismissal Clicking outside the panel or pressing Escape closes it.
Empty state When nothing is due in 48 h: 'All clear' message + next upcoming item shown softly.
Overdue treatment Floated above 'Due Today' section; rendered with red background badge.
Assignment click Opens the Canvas assignment URL in the user's default browser.
First launch Onboarding flow: Canvas URL → token → notification permission → first sync. Under 60
seconds total.
